{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514623","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514623"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:24:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:24:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12341"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12341"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.15,0.56,0.2,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4861"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52053"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4861","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4861"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12341"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37369"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"737"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"1153"},{"type":"tags","id":"2097"},{"type":"tags","id":"3305"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7848"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9766"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10396"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14816"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52053"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a one-week history of double vision. Three days ago, he noticed slurring of his speech and difficulty swallowing. Yesterday, he developed impaired balance. He reports an episode of severe diarrhoea two weeks ago but is otherwise in good health. He does not smoke and drinks alcohol socially. He takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 116/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Neurological examination reveals limitation of eye movement laterally and upwards, and bilateral ptosis. His pupils are equal and reactive. His speech is slurred, and he has sluggish palate movements. Muscle power is normal, but deep tendon reflexes are absent in the upper and lower limbs. Heel-to-shin testing is abnormal, and tandem gait is severely impaired. Investigations reveal a normal complete blood count and comprehensive metabolic panel. Urine toxicology screens are negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Polymyositis","Botulism","Miller Fisher syndrome","Myasthenia gravis","Wernicke\u0027s encephalopathy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of ophthalmoplegia, ataxia, and areflexia, making \u003Cstrong\u003EMiller Fisher syndrome (MFS)\u003C/strong\u003E the most likely diagnosis. MFS is a variant of Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome (GBS) and is an acute post-infection autoimmune neuropathy. The patient\u0027s history of a gastrointestinal illness two weeks prior is consistent with the typical antecedent infection seen in MFS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolymyositis\u003C/strong\u003E is an autoimmune inflammatory myopathy characterized by progressive, symmetrical proximal muscle weakness. It rarely involves extraocular movements and does not typically present with ataxia. The preserved muscle power in this patient, along with the presence of ophthalmoplegia and ataxia, makes polymyositis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBotulism\u003C/strong\u003E can cause ophthalmologic and bulbar signs similar to those seen in this patient. However, the absence of a history of ingesting home-canned foods and the lack of dilated, poorly reactive pupils make botulism less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMyasthenia gravis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with diplopia, ptosis, and bulbar weakness, similar to this patient\u0027s symptoms. However, the weakness in myasthenia gravis is typically fluctuating and fatigable, whereas in MFS, it progressively worsens until reaching a nadir. Additionally, deep tendon reflexes are usually preserved in myasthenia gravis, unlike the areflexia seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EWernicke\u0027s encephalopathy\u003C/strong\u003E presents with a triad of confusion, ocular abnormalities, and ataxia. It is often associated with alcohol abuse or other causes of malnutrition. The absence of confusion, a negative toxicology screen, and lack of history suggesting an underlying etiology make this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn MFS, anti-GQ1b antibodies are found in over 90% of patients and serve as an excellent diagnostic marker. These antibodies target gangliosides on cranial and peripheral nerves, resulting from molecular mimicry between these gangliosides and similar structures on the surface of the infectious agent. Treatment for MFS is the same as for GBS, typically involving intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIg) or plasmapheresis. Recovery usually begins in 2-4 weeks, with near-complete resolution of symptoms within six months.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Miller Fisher syndrome (MFS) is characterized by the triad of ophthalmoplegia, ataxia, and areflexia.","MFS is a variant of Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome and typically follows a gastrointestinal or respiratory infection.","Anti-GQ1b antibodies are present in over 90% of MFS cases and serve as an excellent diagnostic marker."],"references":["Snyder LA, Rismondo V, Miller NR. The Fisher variant of Guillain-Barr\u00e9 syndrome (Fisher syndrome). J Neuroophthalmol. 2009 Dec ;29(4):312\u201324. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/19952907/","Sarwar A, Dydyk AM, Jatwani S. Polymyositis. In: StatPearls [Internet]. 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK563129/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37369"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12341"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37369"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-02T10:35:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-02T10:37:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4861"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52053"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id